ðŸŸ¢ Beginner Level Patterns

ðŸ”¹ 1. Declaration & Scope Patterns
	
	var, let, const

		Function declarations vs expressions

		Block vs function vs global scope

ðŸ”¹ 2. Hoisting Pattern

	Variables (var is hoisted, let/const in TDZ)

	Functions (declarations hoisted, expressions not)

ðŸ”¹ 3. Closure Pattern

Functions retain access to the outer scope even after that scope has returned

function outer() {
  let counter = 0;
  return function () {
    return ++counter;
  };
}
ðŸ”¹ 4. Immediately Invoked Function Expression (IIFE)

	Used to create isolated scopes and avoid polluting global scope

(function () {
  console.log("Executed Immediately");
})();

ðŸ”¹ 5. Module Pattern (Basic)
Simulates private/public access with closures

js
Copy
Edit
const counter = (function () {
  let count = 0;
  return {
    increment: () => ++count,
    get: () => count
  };
})();
ðŸŸ¡ Intermediate Level Patterns
ðŸ”¹ 6. Revealing Module Pattern
Clearly defines what is private and public

js
Copy
Edit
const api = (function () {
  let data = [];
  function add(item) { data.push(item); }
  function list() { return [...data]; }
  return { add, list };
})();
ðŸ”¹ 7. Factory Pattern
Creates objects without using classes

js
Copy
Edit
function createUser(name) {
  return {
    name,
    greet() {
      return `Hi, I'm ${name}`;
    }
  };
}
ðŸ”¹ 8. Constructor Pattern
Used with new keyword to instantiate objects

js
Copy
Edit
function User(name) {
  this.name = name;
  this.greet = function () {
    return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
  };
}
ðŸ”¹ 9. Prototype Pattern
Shares methods across instances efficiently

js
Copy
Edit
User.prototype.greet = function () {
  return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
};
ðŸ”¹ 10. Singleton Pattern
Restricts instantiation to one object

js
Copy
Edit
const Singleton = (function () {
  let instance;
  function create() {
    return { timestamp: Date.now() };
  }
  return {
    getInstance: () => instance || (instance = create())
  };
})();
ðŸ”´ Advanced Level Patterns
ðŸ”¹ 11. Observer Pattern
Subscriber gets notified on state changes (pub-sub)

js
Copy
Edit
class EventEmitter {
  constructor() {
    this.events = {};
  }
  on(event, listener) {
    (this.events[event] ||= []).push(listener);
  }
  emit(event, ...args) {
    (this.events[event] || []).forEach(fn => fn(...args));
  }
}
ðŸ”¹ 12. Strategy Pattern
Swap algorithms at runtime

js
Copy
Edit
const sorter = {
  strategy: null,
  setStrategy(fn) { this.strategy = fn; },
  sort(arr) { return this.strategy(arr); }
};
ðŸ”¹ 13. Command Pattern
Encapsulates actions as objects (e.g., undo/redo)

ðŸ”¹ 14. Proxy Pattern
Intercepts operations on objects

js
Copy
Edit
const target = { msg: "Hello" };
const handler = {
  get(obj, prop) {
    return prop in obj ? obj[prop] : "Not Found";
  }
};
const proxy = new Proxy(target, handler);
ðŸ”¹ 15. Decorator Pattern
Dynamically extends functionality

js
Copy
Edit
function withTimestamp(fn) {
  return function (...args) {
    console.log("Time:", Date.now());
    return fn(...args);
  };
}
ðŸ”¹ 16. Functional Patterns
Pure functions, currying, composition, immutability

js
Copy
Edit
const add = x => y => x + y; // currying
